.SH POSTING CONTENT
How ix.io handles different input methods:
.SS File Posting
.RS
.EX
# Single file
ix.io script.sh
# Output: url: http://ix.io/ABC123

# Multiple files
ix.io file1.txt file2.txt
# Combines files with headers
.EE
.IP \(bu 2
Single file: Posted as-is with filename
.IP \(bu 2
Multiple files: Combined with headers and footers
.IP \(bu 2
File headers: ### Contents from file: /path/to/file
.IP \(bu 2
File footers: ### End of the file from: /path/to/file
.IP \(bu 2
Automatic temp file management
.RE
.SS Directory Posting
.RS
.EX
# Post all files from directory
ix.io --dir /path/to/dir
.EE
.IP \(bu 2
Iterates all files in directory
.IP \(bu 2
Combines files with header/footer markers
.IP \(bu 2
Skips subdirectories by default
.IP \(bu 2
Creates single paste with all content
.RE
.SS Stdin/Pipe Posting
.RS
.EX
# From pipe
cat script.sh | ix.io

# From command output
ls -la | ix.io

# From heredoc
ix.io << EOF
Line 1
Line 2
EOF
.EE
.IP \(bu 2
Reads from stdin if no file arguments
.IP \(bu 2
Detects pipe with [ -p "/dev/stdin" ]
.IP \(bu 2
Writes to temp file before posting
.IP \(bu 2
Automatic content detection
.RE
.SS Direct Text Posting
.RS
.EX
# Post text as arguments
ix.io "Line 1" "Line 2" "Line 3"
.EE
.IP \(bu 2
Each argument becomes a line
.IP \(bu 2
Writes to temp file before posting
.IP \(bu 2
Useful for quick text snippets
.IP \(bu 2
No need for quotes (bash handles escaping)
.RE
